mb|p|sk|s|NT||lb|*bWhat should South bid?^^3n|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|On most hands, responder is captain, meaning they are responsible for getting their side to the correct contract. However, when you have a max opener (18+), once partner responds, showing at least 6, then you assume responsibility for getting to game. Because you know that your side has enough points for game. When responder is captain, it is fairly easy to make forcing bids to keep the auction going. |
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|New suits by responder are always forcing, so opener may not pass a responder's new suit. On the other hand, despite misconceptions by some people, simple new suits by opener are |cp|8|at|NOT |cp||at|forcing. For example, if I bid 2C, that is not forcing. TJ can and should pass with a min hand and clubs, such as the hand she holds. Opener's forcing bids are reverses (2S is the only reverse available on this auction), and jump shifts. |
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Jump shifts establish a game force. If I jump shift (3C or 3D), the auction cannot stop below game. That is because a jump shift shows 18+, so we must have enough points for game. A reverse is slightly different. It can be done with fewer points (16 or so). It does establish a one round force for responder, but does not establish a game force.|
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|On this hand, I am simply going to bid 3N. Some of you would be worried about diamonds. But it usually pays to be optimistic :). Don't worry too much about bidding 3N with a singleton or even void, especially if pard has shown some values in the suit. People worry too much about bidding 3N with shortness.|mb|3N|
