^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let's talk about Joan's 2nd lead in spades. When partner leads a suit, and you win the first trick and lead it back you lead back your "remaining count." On this hand, Joan had Qxx of spades left after winning the SA. Therefore, she leads low from 3 spade. If she had a doubleton left, she would have led high.|
PG| ***** 48 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|For example, on the last hand, Bonnie started with A8x of diamonds. After winning the DA, she played back the D8, to show she had a doubleton left (her lead showed her "remaining count"). Once you learn to count out suits, leading back remaining count is very useful. |
PG| ***** 49 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|For example, on this hand, when Joan led back the S5, that means, since it is the lowest one out, that she started with either A5 or AQx5 of spades and she did not start out with 3 spades.|
PG| ***** 50 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Therefore, Bonnie can count out the spades. If Joan started with 4, that means I started with 2. If Joan started with 2, then I started with 4. You should get in the habit, when you can, of counting out suits on defense and having partner lead back remaining count helps you tremendously in figuring out how many declarer started with.|
