qx|B5|pn|hondo717,tjtoo (TJ),boater (Joan),bjmue (Bonnie)|st||sk|W|md|3S57KH35TJQD46QC8J,S4689QAH28D78TCTA,S3TH49AD39JC235QK,|rh||ah|Board 5|sv|n|mb|p|mb|p|mb|p|lb|*mWhich would be you choice of bid here?^1S~2S~Pass~Either 1S or 2S~I have no clue^4|mb|1S|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|This is an interesting bidding hand. The issue is, what does a 2S opener mean in 4th seat? First of all, it is not a classic Weak-2. The idea of a weak 2 is to make it hard for the opponents, who presumably have more points from getting to their best contract. In 4th seat, if you pass, then you have prevented the opponents from getting to their best spot :). Therefore, opening 2S in 4th seat definitely does not show 5-10 and a 6-card suit. |
PG| ***** 105 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|There are 2 schools of thought on what it should show. The more mainstream method is it shows a minish hand (11-14 HCP or so) with a nice suit. The Marty Bergen theory is it shows 9-12 instead of 11-14. I would have probably passed with TJ's hand, as I use the more mainstream theory, although with Bergen starting points, it does evaluate to 11 due to the Aces and Tens. |
PG| ***** 106 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Using the Bergen theory TJ can open 2S. Even some mainstream experts would open 2S. Some use the rule of 15, which also works on this hand (HCP + spade length at least 15). I am not a big believer in the rule of 15, nor are most experts. As many of you know, I believe in rule of 20 in all seats. You need to pick the style that works best for you.|
PG| ***** 107 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The hand does not meet the rule of 20, unless you adjusted for your 4 Aces and 10s, it has 10 HCP and 9 in spades and diamonds. You cannot count length points in rule of 20. That is an important point. When using the rule of 20, even if you use Bergen hand evaluation rules, you do not count length. The rule of 20 takes care of length when it counts the length of your 2 longest suits. If you also used it as part of Bergen hand evaluation you would be counting length twice. |
PG| ***** 108 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|What Bergen says about the HCP part of the rule of 20 is you use "adjusted HCP" which means you use the other 4 starting point rules (HCP, quality suits, dubious shortness, adjust3) but not length to calculate your HCP. So TJ's hand has 11 "adjusted" HCP, 10 HCP plus 1 points for 4 ace/tens. Enough to open 1S using the rule of 20. But 2S is still a good opening bid  with that hand in 4th seat. The points must be evenly spread out, so it is good to make it hard for the opponents to compete.|
