Generally all should go smoothly when your partner opens 1NT, or 2NT, or opens 2C and rebids 2N and the opponents stay out of bidding. |
PG| ***** 149 ***** |


AT|

After a 1NT opening, the options available for responder, based on distribution and strength are 2N, 2C (Stayman), 2D/2H (transfer to majors), 2S (transfer to minors - notwithstanding 4-way transfers), 3C/3D (invitation to 3N), and 3H/3S (forcing to game/invitation to slam), 4D/4H (Texas transfer to majors). Responder's option after a 2NT bid or 2C with 2NT rebid are very similar - Stayman, transfers and etc.|
PG| ***** 150 ***** |


AT|

On the other hand when the opponents make a direct double or overcall a 1NT or 2NT things get a bit problematic. In majority of instances the reason is lack of previous understanding between the partners as how to handle the interference after a NT opening.|
PG| ***** 151 ***** |


AT|

Experts use different methods to handle such interference. Lebensohl is probably the most comprehensive one. However, it is very complicated and not easy for average partnerships to adopt. On the other hand, there are other methods which a partnership can adopt and be able to defend against the interference and avoid 99% of mishaps.|
PG| ***** 152 ***** |


AT|

In this tutorial we plan to present in detail the method Howard recommends and seems fully acceptable by many other experts. For ease of understanding here we divide the interference into:

^CWhen the NT bid is DOUBLED
^CWhen the NT is OVERCALLED|
PG| ***** 153 ***** |


AT|

Knowing whether the interference is conventional or natural is important but is not essential. Regardless, it is not the aim of this tutorial to address the nature of interference after NT openings. So without further ado let us look at some examples. In the following examples after partner opens NT, first we deal with responder's option in uncontested bidding followed by options after an immediate double.|
PG| ***** 154 ***** |


